{meta: title A Long Way From Montana}
{meta: artist Red Steagall}
{meta: composer R.W. Hampton, Phil Martin, Red Steagall}

{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[C]A long [Em]way it [F]is from Montana
To [C]west Texas whether by [D7]hoof or by [G7]rail
A [C]long [Em]way it [F]is from Alzada
To [C]innocence [Am]lost somewhere [G7]out on the [C]trail
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
And my [Em]heart is [F]lonesome and longin'
My [C]comrades are gone on the [D7]first morning [G7]train
And [C]my [Em]heart hears a [F]boyhood hymn callin'
From a [C]church down the [Am]valley comes [G7]this old re[C]frain
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
Softly and tenderly [F]Jesus is [C]calling
[Am]Calling for [D7]you and for [G7]me
[C]See on the portals He's [F]waiting and [C]watching
[Am]Watching for [G7]you and for [C]me
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
Too [Em]many [F]autumns I've watched 'em
Board [C]trains with their plunder all [D7]headed for [G7]home
And [C]too [Em]many [F]autumns I've stayed here
To [C]snap out the [Am]new ones fore [G7]winter comes [C]on
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 5}
And I [Em]wonder [F]who's waiting for them
A [C]sweetheart or lover or [D7]young wife with [G7]babe
[C]But I [Em]know [F]who's waiting for me
A [C]mother and father who's [G7]hair has turned [C]grey
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 6}
Come [G7]home come [C]home
A [G7]wandering [D7]cowboy come [G7]home
[C]Earnestly tenderly [F]I hear them [C]calling
My son it's [G7]time to come [C]home
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 7}
I've [Em]lingered [F]long in this country
From [C]high thunder basin to [D7]where rim lands [G7]start
[C]I've [Em]lingered [F]too long a sinner
It's [C]time that I [Am]pack up and [G7]follow my [C]heart
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 8}
A long [Em]way it [F]is from Alzada
To a [C]little sod house on the [D7]west Texas [G7]plains
[C]A long [Em]way it [F]is from Montana
[C]But I'm going [F]home on the [G7]next southbound [C]train
A long [Em]way it [F]is from Mon[C]tana
{end_of_verse}
